**Where do you go to connect with nature?**
---

**[Riverbrook Preserve](https://www.midcoastconservancy.org/preserves-directory/riverbrook-preserve),** managed by Midcoast Conservancy, is a great place for an easy hike (or  
cross-country ski or snowshoe) on a nearly 400-acre parcel of land that has open fields, deep  
woods and beautiful meandering river frontage on the Medomak River.

[![](https://www.pressherald.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2026/01/Pinky2.jpg?w=480)](https://w2pcms.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/10/2026/01/Pinky2.jpg)

Pinky LaRue in Waldoboro, selling “fashionably vintage” housewares, home decore and more. (Photo courtesy of Pinky LaRue.)

**Where do you go to shop local?**
---

After you’ve gone to Riverbrook Preserve, you have to head to **[Morse’s Sauerkraut,](https://www.morsessauerkraut.com/)** a half-mile up the road. Besides their world-famous kraut, it’s a great place for unique stocking stuffers, a hard-to-find bottle of wine for a host gift, or the best “girl dinner.” Get some world-class cheese at [**East Forty Farm**](https://www.lakinsgorgescheese.com/east-forty-farm) and go eat it on the picnic tables down at the [**town landing**](https://cms9files.revize.com/waldoborome/2021%20Town%20Flyer.pdf) while you watch the tide change and think about how sweet Waldoboro is. Go to [**Delano Seafood**](https://www.delanoseafoodmarket.com/) for the clams — Waldoboro is one of the leading clam harvesting ports in Maine — for sure, but their huge selection of fresh and frozen seafood, beer and wine, and Maine Made gifts is fantastic.

**What’s a hidden gem in Waldoboro?**
---

I love [**Pinky La Rue**](https://pinky-larue.square.site/) for a wildly good curated selection of vintage clothing, vinyl and housewares. The owner, Natalie, is the coolest.

